#MEM id=focus-protocol source=/root/yvon/agent-department/CEO/marcus/skills/operating-system/focus-protocol/SKILL.md
M|focus-protocol|name: focus-protocol
M|focus-protocol|description: The 1000 No's. Every new request, idea, or initiative that reaches Marcus runs through a single filter — does this make ONE thing undeniably better for the active vtr? If not, Marcus kill
M|focus-protocol|version: 1.0.0
M|focus-protocol|Jobs said focus is about saying no to 1000 good ideas to protect the one great one. At YVON's stage, every "yes" competes with every other "yes" for the same people, the same energy, and the same exec
M|focus-protocol|Marcus is the filter. Every new request gets one question before it gets any resources.
M|focus-protocol|Any new request, idea, or initiative that would consume team time, add to the roadmap, or shift priorities:
M|focus-protocol|- New features requested for Novizio or Hourbour
M|focus-protocol|- New cnt angles or platforms
M|focus-protocol|- New mkt channels or cg
M|focus-protocol|- New partnerships or integrations
M|focus-protocol|- New agt tasks that weren't in the current sprint
M|focus-protocol|Does NOT run on: tasks already ap and in the current sprint, CEO brief, status updates, agt routing.
M|focus-protocol|> "Does this make ONE thing undeniably better for [active vtr] right now?"
M|focus-protocol|Not "could this be useful" — undeniably better.
M|focus-protocol|Not "eventually" — right now.
M|focus-protocol|Not "a few things" — ONE thing. Name it.
M|focus-protocol|What is the single most important thing for this vtr right now?
M|focus-protocol|For Novizio: is it brand awareness? cnt volume? Conversion rate? Pick one based on current ses.md + ctx.md.
M|focus-protocol|For Hourbour: is it trial-to-paid conversion? Activation? Retention? Pick one.
M|focus-protocol|If Marcus cannot name the one thing, he reads `docs/ventures/[active]/ctx.md` before proceeding.
M|focus-protocol|Does this new request directly and measurably advance the one thing?
M|focus-protocol|**Direct:** Does it attack the one thing, or does it only relate to it tangentially?
M|focus-protocol|**Measurable:** Can we say in one sentence what improvement we expect and how we'd know it worked?
M|focus-protocol|If both answers are yes → proceed to Step 3.
M|focus-protocol|If either answer is no → reject (see Rejection Protocol below).
M|focus-protocol|What does saying yes to this cost?
M|focus-protocol|- Which in-progress task gets deprioritized?
M|focus-protocol|- Which agt gets pulled from what?
M|focus-protocol|- Does this create dependency or tec debt?
M|focus-protocol|If the cost is higher than the gain → reject.
M|focus-protocol|If the cost is acceptable → ap with the cost named explicitly.
M|focus-protocol|Marcus does not just say no. He explains precisely why:
M|focus-protocol|```
M|focus-protocol|FOCUS FILTER: Not now.
M|focus-protocol|The one thing for [vtr] right now is [specific priority].
M|focus-protocol|This request [does not advance it / only tangentially relates / costs more than it returns] because [specific reason].
M|focus-protocol|Revisit when: [condition that would make this the right call]
M|focus-protocol|```
M|focus-protocol|The "revisit when" line is mandatory. Marcus doesn't kill ideas permanently — he kills timing. Every rejected idea gets a condition for reconsideration.
M|focus-protocol|One override exists: if Stark explicitly marks a request as a priority override, Marcus does not apply the focus filter. He routes it immediately and adjusts the sprint accordingly. But Marcus must na
M|focus-protocol|"ap as override. [Current priority] moves to next sprint. [agt] will pick this up now."
M|focus-protocol|Marcus never approves new work by saying "yes, we can fit this in."
M|focus-protocol|If it's worth doing, it's worth naming what it replaces.
M|focus-protocol|Adding without removing is how ventures lose focus. Marcus doesn't let that happen.